{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.48,0.15,0.14,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111246"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111246"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 49-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of severe headaches and worsening shortness of breath. The headaches are constant, throbbing, and associated with photophobia but no focal neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her regular medication is omeprazole as needed. She works as an office administrator and smokes five cigarettes per day; there is no recent travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 117/min, blood pressure 210/115 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral inspiratory crackles to the mid zones. There is no focal neurological deficit. Hand examination findings are shown below (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xWl2SbcVBn5uxgpNcrGTpOgMKYeKE2.jpg\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImage\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 97 g/L (120-150)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 8.8 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 87 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine 289 \u00b5mol/L (50-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase 680 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaptoglobin 0.1 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect antiglobulin test negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood film shows numerous schistocytes and polychromasia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Scleroderma renal crisis","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome","Hypertensive nephrosclerosis","Systemic lupus erythematosus nephritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScleroderma renal crisis is a life-threatening emergency characterised by abrupt severe hypertension, acute kidney injury, and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia in people with diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis. Recognition hinges on integrating clinical context with laboratory evidence of haemolysis and thrombocytopenia. Early treatment with angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors improves renal and survival outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma renal crisis\u003C/strong\u003E best fits the combination of sudden severe hypertension, rising creatinine, thrombocytopenia, and microangiopathic haemolysis (schistocytes, high lactate dehydrogenase, low haptoglobin, negative direct antiglobulin test). The accompanying pulmonary crackles are consistent with hypertensive pulmonary oedema from acute renal impairment. Although the cutaneous manifestations are not described here, the constellation of malignant hypertension with microangiopathic haemolysis and acute kidney injury is classic for this diagnosis in a person who may have underlying systemic sclerosis features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E can cause microangiopathic haemolysis and thrombocytopenia with renal involvement, but it is more often marked by prominent neurological features and fever. The severe accelerated hypertension and pulmonary oedema point away from this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E produces a triad of microangiopathic haemolysis, thrombocytopenia, and kidney injury, typically following a prodrome of bloody diarrhoea in shiga toxin-associated disease or in complement-mediated forms without severe malignant hypertension. The absence of a gastrointestinal prodrome and the presence of marked hypertension make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive nephrosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic process due to long-standing hypertension, leading to gradual decline in kidney function without a marked microangiopathic haemolytic picture. It does not explain the abrupt onset of severe hypertension with schistocytosis and thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause renal impairment and cytopenias, but there are no clinical features of systemic lupus erythematosus in the history or examination, and lupus nephritis would not typically present with sudden malignant hypertension and overt microangiopathic haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scleroderma renal crisis presents with abrupt severe hypertension, acute kidney injury, and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia in people with diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis.","Early angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor therapy is critical and improves outcomes in scleroderma renal crisis.","Blood film schistocytes with raised lactate dehydrogenase, low haptoglobin, and a negative direct antiglobulin test indicate microangiopathic haemolysis."],"references":["Volkmann ER, Andr\u00e9asson K, Smith V. Systemic sclerosis. Lancet. 2023 Jan 28;401(10373):304-318. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36442487/","Maria Sieglinda von Nudeldorf, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22640"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22027"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22027"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.